07293nam a22015015i 9780691226521DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021012744  a(OCoLC)1302163396  a97806912265217 a10.1515/97806912265212doi  a(DE-B1597)600732  a(OCoLC)1301547992  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aNA2707.S27bB76 2022 7aART0150802bisacsh04a720.937qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aBrothers, Cammy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGiuliano da Sangallo and the Ruins of Rome /cCammy Brothers. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b211 color + 53 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tAcknowledgments and Note to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Architect as Bookmaker -- t2. What Is Antique? -- t3. Ornament and Abstraction -- t4. Ruins and Representation -- t5. Research, Reconstruction, and Design -- tEpilogue: Rome Remade -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Folios -- tGeneral Index -- tPhotography and Copyright Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn illuminating reassessment of the architect whose innovative drawings of ruins shaped the enduring image of ancient RomeGiuliano da Sangallo (1443–1516) was one of the first architects to draw the ruins and artifacts of ancient Rome in a systematic way. Cammy Brothers shows how Giuliano played a crucial role in the Renaissance recovery of antiquity, and how his work transformed the broken fragments of Rome's past into the image of a city made whole.Drawing new insights from the Codex Barberini and the Taccuino Senese—two exquisite collections of Giuliano's drawings on parchment—Brothers reveals how the Florentine architect devoted enormous energy to the representation of ruins, and how his studies of Rome formed an integral part of his work as a designer. She argues that Giuliano's inventive approach, which has often been mischaracterized as fantastical or naive, infused the architect's craft with the sensibilities of a poet and painter. Brothers demonstrates how his drawings form the basis for a reevaluation of the meaning and method of the Renaissance study of ancient artifacts, and brings to life the transformative moment when artists and architects began to view the fragments of ancient Rome not as broken artifacts of little interest but as objects of aesthetic contemplation.Featuring a wealth of Giuliano's magnificent drawings, this compelling book provides an incomparable lens through which to explore essential questions about the aesthetic value, significance, and the uses of the past for today's architects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecture, RomanxAppreciation. 0aArchitecture, Roman, in art. 0aClassical antiquities in art. 0aRuins in art. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAncient Roman architecture.  aAncient Rome.  aAncient monument.  aAndrea Mantegna.  aAndrea Palladio.  aAntonio Labacco.  aArch of Constantine.  aBaldassare Castiglione.  aBaldassare Peruzzi.  aBasilica Aemilia.  aBasilica of Santa Maria Novella.  aBaths of Diocletian.  aBenvenuto Cellini.  aBernardo Rossellino.  aCalumny of Apelles (Botticelli).  aCassiano dal Pozzo.  aCornice.  aDante Alighieri.  aDe Re Aedificatoria.  aDomenico Ghirlandaio.  aDonatello.  aEntablature.  aFilippino Lippi.  aFilippo Brunelleschi.  aFlavio Biondo.  aFlorence Cathedral.  aFrancesco di Giorgio Martini.  aGiacomo Barozzi da Vignola.  aGiotto.  aGiuliano da Maiano.  aGiuliano da Sangallo.  aGiulio Romano.  aI quattro libri dell'architettura.  aIllustration. 